        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-10-30T16:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-10-30T16:54:00-05:00" n="144"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d144">
                <head>144. Memorandum of a Telephone Conversation Between the President and the
                    Secretary of State, Washington, October 30, 1956, 4:54 p.m.<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d144fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> Papers, White House Telephone Conversations.
                        Transcribed by <persName corresp="#p_BPD1">Bernau</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1956-10-30T16:54:00-05:00"
                            >October 30, 1956, 4:54 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">TELEPHONE CALL FROM THE PRESIDENT</p>
                <p>The Pres. read his answer to <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName>.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d144fn2">For text of <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName>’s draft message to <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                            >Eden</persName>, see <ref target="frus1955-57v16#pg_874">vol. XVI, p.
                            874</ref>. The message was not sent.</note> The Sec. said what a great
                    tragedy it is just when the whole Soviet policy is collapsing the Br and Fr are
                    doing the same thing in the Arab world. The Pres. referred to what he said in
                    the letter re there being no colonialism. He may add he certainly hopes we don’t
                    get in the position the Soviets are in in Hungary. The Pres. will send it
                    over.</p>
            </div>
